<doc id="1179451" wikidata="Q810255" url="?curid=1179451" title="Change of basis">
<text>In mathematics, an ordered basis of a vector space of finite dimension allows representing uniquely any element of the vector space by a coordinate vector, which is a sequence of scalars called coordinates. If two different bases are considered, the coordinate vector that represents a vector on one basis is, in general, different from the coordinate vector that represents on the other basis. A change of basis consists of converting every assertion expressed in terms of coordinates relative to one basis into an assertion expressed in terms of coordinates relative to the other basis.

Such a conversion results from the &quot;change-of-basis formula&quot; which expresses the coordinates relative to one basis in terms of coordinates relative to the other basis. Using matrices, this formula can be written
:formula_1
where &quot;old&quot; and &quot;new&quot; refer respectively to the initially defined basis and the other basis, formula_2 and formula_3 are the column vectors of the coordinates of the same vector on the two bases. formula_4 is the change-of-basis matrix (also called transition matrix), which is the matrix whose columns are the coordinates of the new basis vectors on the old basis.

A change of basis is sometimes called a &quot;change of coordinates&quot;, although it excludes many coordinate transformations.
For applications in physics and specially in mechanics, a change of basis often involves the transformation of an orthonormal basis, understood as a rotation in physical space, thus excluding translations.
This article deals mainly with finite-dimensional vector spaces. However, many of the principles are also valid for infinite-dimensional vector spaces.

==Change of basis formula==
Let formula_5 be a basis of a finite-dimensional vector space over a field .

For , one can define a vector by its coordinates formula_6 over formula_7
:formula_8

Let
:formula_9
be the matrix whose th column is formed by the coordinates of . (Here and in what follows, the index refers always to the rows of and the formula_10 while the index refers always to the columns of and the formula_11 such a convention is useful for avoiding errors in explicit computations.)

Setting formula_12 one has that formula_13 is a basis of if and only if the matrix is invertible, or equivalently if it has a nonzero determinant. In this case, is said to be the &quot;change-of-basis matrix&quot; from the basis formula_14 to the basis formula_15

Given a vector formula_16 let formula_17 be the coordinates of formula_18 over formula_19 and formula_20 its coordinates over formula_21 that is 
:formula_22
(One could take the same summation index for the two sums, but choosing systematically the indexes for the old basis and for the new one makes clearer the formulas that follows, and helps avoiding errors in proofs and explicit computations.)

The &quot;change-of-basis formula&quot; expresses the coordinates over the old basis in terms of the coordinates over the new basis. With above notation, it is
:formula_23

In terms of matrices, the change of basis formula is
:formula_24
where formula_25 and formula_26 are the column vectors of the coordinates of over formula_14 and formula_28 respectively.

&quot;Proof:&quot; Using the above definition of the change-of basis matrix, one has
:formula_29

As formula_30 the change-of-basis formula results from the uniqueness of the decomposition of a vector over a basis.

